	abstract = {Positively and negatively charged nanoparticles have been mixed together in order to obtain superlattice formation. The interaction between the particles was controlled by adjusting the ionic strength of the solutions. The self-assembly was studied with absorption spectroscopy, powder X-ray diffraction, and high-resolution transmission electron microscopy. During the 80s and 90s nanoparticle research focused on the synthesis of nanoclusters of different sizes and on investigating the size dependence of the particle properties. 1,2 Now methods of building macroscopic solids consisting of two-or three-dimensional periodic structures of nanoparticles and the properties of such nanoparticle assemblies attract more attention. 3-5 This new class of materials has interesting electronic, optical, optoelectronic, and magnetic properties. Molecular crystals of II-VI semiconductor nanoclusters (CdS, CdSe, HgSe) could be synthesized and the atomic-level structure information of these clusters could be determined by single-crystal X-ray diffraction measurements. 6-10 Larger semiconductor particles with very narrow size distributions can form colloidal crystals (CdSe). 11,12 Metal nanoparticles (Au, Ag) with narrow size distributions form 2D or 3D nanoparticle arrays. 13-16 The main driving force of superlattice formation in all these cases is the van der Waals interaction between the ligands of the particles. Another strategy is chemical cross-linking between nano-particles, which results in stable superlattices, but typically without long-range order. 17,18 There are also approaches to use the Coulomb interaction to achieve the self-assembly of nanoparticles. Multilayers of charged nanoparticles could be formed using electrostatic interaction between the nanopar-ticles and oppositely charged cross-linkers such as small molecules, 19-21 polymers, 22-25 or other nanoparticles. 26 The aggregation of negatively charged Au and positively charged SiO 2 particles in solution was also shown, but only amorphous structures could be formed in this way. 27 Attractive electrostatic interaction results in a fast agglomeration and makes it difficult to achieve an ordered, periodic three-dimensional structure. We present here an approach to obtain self-organization of nanoparticles with electrostatic interaction and to control the forces between the particles to improve the process of superlattice formation. The particles used in this approach are positively and negatively charged cadmium sulfide nanoclusters, about 2 nm in diameter, and negatively charged gold nanocrystals, 12 nm in diameter. The charged particles are obtained by modifying the surface with anionic and cationic thiol compounds (Scheme 1a). Their self-assembly has been investigated by powder X-ray diffraction (XRD) and transmission electron microscopy (TEM). Two possibilities of nanoparticle self-assembly will be shown here (Scheme 1b). With a large excess of one kind of particles inorganic complex-like structures arise. The positively and negatively charged nanoparticles are the analogues to the central ion and ligands in coordination chemistry. The other possibility is to mix comparable amounts of positively and negatively charged nanoparticles in order to obtain a 3D ordered solid consisting of nanopar-ticles. The results of slow and fast precipitation will be compared with each other. The synthesis of thiol stabilized cadmium sulfide particles known from literature 28 was modified to obtain positively and negatively charged particles. PositiVely Charged CdS Nanoparticles (pCdS). A 2 g sample of cadmium perchlorate hexahydrate and 3 g of 2-(dimethylamino)ethanthiol hydrochloride were dissolved in 250 mL water. The pH value was adjusted to 5.0 with 1 M NaOH solution. A 50 mL aliquot of H 2 S was injected under vigorous stirring. After having been stirred 2 days at room temperature, the solution was dialyzed against water. NegatiVely Charged CdS Nanoparticles (nCdS). A 2 g sample of cadmium perchlorate hexahydrate and 2 mL of 3-mercaptopropionic acid were dissolved in 250 mL of water. The pH value was adjusted to 11.2 with 1 M NaOH solution. A 50 mL aliquot of H 2 S was injected under vigorous stirring. The solution turned yellow. Then 1 M HClO 4 was added until a pH value of 6 was reached. The solution turned colorless while it was refluxed for 6 h. The byproducts were removed by dialysis against water.},
