int around 850 nm indicates the existence of both isolated and assembled Au nanorods. Figure 1B shows a representative TEM image of the nanorods assembled in the presence of 1 mM of MPA at pH ¼ 9.6. The nanorods are preferentially linked together at their ends. The red-shifted longitudinal plasmon peak therefore arises from the coupling of the longitudinal plasmon resonance between EE-assembled Au nanorods. The EE assembly process is found to be dependent on time. The longitudinal plasmon peak intensity of unassembled nanorods gets weaker and the coupled plasmon peak intensity becomes stronger with increasing time (Figure S1 of Supporting Information), suggesting that the number of EE-assembled nanorods increases with time. Eventually all nanorods are assembled and precipitate to the bottom of the solution, which precludes the measurement of extinction spectra. In order to compare the assembling behavior under different conditions, we therefore keep the assembling time to 2 h. The dependence of the nanorod assembly on the pH provides a means for reversibly controlling the assembly and disassembly of Au nanorods. Nanorods EE assembled in the presence of MPA at pH above \%8.0 can be disassembled by adjusting the pH to below \%8.0. Ultrasonication can accelerate the disassembly of nanorods (Figure S2A of Supporting Information). Figure 1C shows the extinction spectra of four cycles of the assembly and disassembly of Au nanorods, where the assembly was carried out at pH ¼ 9.6 and the disassembly was carried out by ultrasonication at pH ¼ 3.1 for 20 min. The extinction spectrum recorded after the disassembly process is very close in shape to that of the initial nanorod solution, [ Ã ] Prof.},
