	abstract = {1. Synthesis of hybrid Au/SiO 2 /CdSe-QD nanostructures Our synthesis developed for hybrid Au/SiO 2 /CdSe-QD nanostructures comprises several sequential steps as described below. 1.1 Synthesis of gold nanoparticle seeds and seeded growth of larger particles Gold nanoparticle seeds were prepared according to the standard sodium citrate reduction method, 1 which produced monodisperse (6\% size dispersion in terms of coefficient of variance (CV)) nanoparticles of a nearly perfect spherical shape (Figure S1). Specifically, 350 ml of H 2 O and 200 ml of 0.219 mM HAuCl 4 aqueous solutions were mixed in a 1-L flask and were heated to boiling. Then, 100 ml of 1\% sodium citrate solution was quickly added into the boiling mixture. 30 minutes later, the deep-red solution of Au nanoparticles was cooled to room temperature and diluted to a total volume of 615 ml. This procedure produced Au seeds with a mean diameter of 15 nm. In order to grow larger Au particles we used a seeded growth method 2. Specifically, 12 ml of the solution of 15-nm Au seed particles were mixed with 150 ml of H 2 O and 35 ml of 1\% sodium citrate in a 500-ml flask and heated to 70˚C. Then, 120 ml of 0.219 mM HAuCl 4 solution were slowly added to the mixture. 60 minutes later, the solution was cooled to room temperature. The resulting mean Au particle size was 30 nm and the size dispersion was 9\%. The increase in sample polydispersity during the seeded growth is typically observed in the synthesis of gold nanoparticles (see, e.g., Ref. 3). Figure S1. TEM image of the 15-nm Au seed nanoparticles. In order to prepare even larger particles we repeated the above procedure using 30-nm particles as seeds. 1.2 Synthesis of Au/SiO 2 core/shell nanoparticles Au/SiO 2 core/shell nanoparticles were synthesized according to a modified procedure from ref. 3. We used 3-mercaptopropyltrimethoxysilane (MPTMS) instead of 3-aminopropyltrimethoxysilane (APTMS) for activation the gold particle surfaces before the silica shell deposition. After surface activation, an active silica solution was used to deposit a thin layer (4-5 nm) of silica on the gold particles. Then sequential growth method was used to deposit thicker silica shells. S１},
